SpNote.note:
In the thermal its necessary for the standards to have the same exposure as the target, so that non-linearity is not an issue. For this reason the standards here are set to use the largest field field possible on the assumption that the target is being observed in this way. The largest field is the full array for L' and M. For L' either of the waveforms "THERMAL ND" or "THERMAL CDS" is usable in the full array with 0.12"/pix camera; for M, use only "THERMAL CDS" for full array readout in the 0.12"/pix camera. Always use the same waveform for the target and the standard.
If necessary, adjust the configuration of the standard to match your target, but be careful to use appropriate exposures and waveforms - see the web pages.
If your science field is small, efficiency is low in large field mode; for maximum efficiency the 0.06"/pixel camera should be used with the 512x512 subarray.
SpNote.title: Field size and efficiency

SpNote.note:
In the thermal its necessary for the standards to have the same exposure as the target, so that non-linearity is not an issue. The standards here are setup for peak efficiency, using the 0.06"/pixel camera and the 512x512 subarray. Adjust the configuration to match your target but be careful to use appropriate exposures - see the web pages.
The largest field available is with the 0.12"/pixel camera and full array at L', 512x512 at M'. Observations are then very inefficient.
The nod 8 pattern uses the left sideof the array only to avoid the low QE lower right and the sometimes poorly behaved central 100 pixels (which are to the right of the telescope aperture)
SpNote.title: Field size and efficiency
